*Rhymes: [[Rhymes:English:-ɒm|-ɒm]]

===Etymology===
From [[Ancient Greek]] '''[[βόμβος]]''' (''bombos'') "booming, humming, buzzing" (imitative of the sound itself), also from [[Latin]] bombus meaning: a booming sound.

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# A device filled with explosives used for destroying things.
# {{slang}}: A [[failure]]; an unpopular commercial product.
#:* The movie "Ishtar" was a '''bomb'''.
# {{context|AU|colloquial|automotive|vehicles}} A [[car]] in poor condition. Used often as [[old bomb]].
#*'''2005''' August 6, ''Warm affection for a rust-bucket past'', [[w:Sydney Morning Herald|Sydney Morning Herald]] [http://www.smh.com.au/news/words/warm-affection-for-a-rustbucket-past/2005/08/04/1123125839592.html]
#*: Nowadays, an old '''bomb''' simply won't pass the inspection.''
# {{context|chiefly|British|slang}} A [[success]]; [[the bomb]].
#:* Our fabulous new crumpets have been selling like a '''bomb'''.
# {{slang}} A very attractive woman.

====Usage notes====
The diametrical slang meanings are somewhat distinguishable by the article. For "a success", the phrase is generally ''[[the bomb]]''. Otherwise ''bomb'' can mean "a failure".

